<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Papua New Guinea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Cancelled as Rebels Unable To Attend </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Cancelled as Rebels Unable To Attend </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2206085794 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2206085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Papua New Guinea's Prime Minister Paias Wingti has 
revealed that talks between government officials, Bougainville 
leaders, and rebels had been canceled earlier this week because 
the leaders of the Bougainville Revolutionary Army could not 
attend. The Port Moresby based newspaper, THE NATIONAL, says Mr. 
Wingti told us that the Honiara meeting did not go ahead as 
planned because the government decided that Francis Ona and Sam 
Kouna had to be involved. He said the government did not want 
to waste its time by talking to a variety of people and then not 
getting any results. Mr. Wingti reportedly also said that the 
government would not make any announcements until talks between 
the leaders on both sides were over. 

</TEXT>

