<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Western Samoa </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Launches Verbal `Assault' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Launches Verbal `Assault' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2106132594 Hong Kong AFP in English 1317 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2106132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] APIA, June 20 (AFP) -- Western Samoa's dignity had 
been damaged in 1980 by apologizing to Nauru, Prime Minister 
Tofilau Eti Alesana told parliament here Monday. 
  Lashing out at Nauru, he compared its size to that of a 
glass 
of water and said it was a Pacific nation with no honorific 
greetings or genealogy. 
  His assault on phosphate rich Nauru came just two weeks 
after 
Nauru President Bernard Dowiyogo was here for independence 
anniversary celebrations. 
  Tofilau was referring to an incident in 1980 when, under a 
previous government, claims were made that Nauru had funded 
opposition political groups. As a result of the claims, Nauru 
promptly withdrew its investments in Samoa, resulting in an 
apology from the then government of Prime Minister Tupuola Efi, 
who is now Opposition Leader and is known as Tupua Tamasese Efi. 
  The most senior member of the opposition Samoa National 
Development Party present in the house, Ulualofaiga Talamaivao 
Niko, said Monday's remarks by Tofilau were "childish and 
stupid" and would have a damaging impact on relations with "our 
brothers in the Pacific." 
  "If we look down on Nauru because of the size of Nauru, how 
would we feel if countries bigger than Western Samoa did the 
same? ...I'm very ashamed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

