<H3> <TI>   LDP Submits No-Confidence Motion Against Hata </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP Submits No-Confidence Motion Against Hata </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306083694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- The largest opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) submitted a no-confidence motion 
Thursday [23 June] to the House of Representatives against the 
government of Prime Minister Hata shortly after the Diet passed 
the overdue budget for fiscal 1994. 
  The LDP decided to submit the motion during its Executive 
Council meeting Wednesday, saying the government has not made 
sufficient efforts to clarify former Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's suspected personal financial irregularities. 
  If the lower house approves the motion, Hata must either 
resign en masse with his cabinet or dissolve the house for a 
snap general election. 
  But it is not clear whether the LDP will have the support 
from the second largest opposition Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
needed to muster a majority of votes to pass the motion. 
  The SDP, which split from the ruling alliance in April, 
indicated earlier it may join the LDP in pushing the motion but 
displayed willingness Wednesday to mend frayed ties with the 
coalition. 
  Hata and SDP head Tomiichi Murayama were scheduled to meet 
later Thursday to discuss a possible realliance. 
  The LDP and the ruling coalition are courting the SDP since 
both sides are short of a majority in the Diet. 
  The LDP urged the SDP earlier Thursday to hold a meeting of 
the two parties' leaders to discuss a plan to set up a new 
government. 
  The current Diet session ends next Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

