<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition, SDPJ Nearing Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coalition, SDPJ Nearing Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306074094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0728 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- The shaky ruling coalition 
of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and the former partner Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) [of Japan, SDPJ] were nearing agreement 
in their crucial reconciliation talks Thursday [23 June], with 
speculation rife on the probability of Hata's resignation, 
political sources said. 
  Jockeying among key political parties entered the last 
stretch amid a looming possibility of agreement on realliance 
being reached at a meeting later in the day between Hata and SDP 
Chairman Tomiichi Murayama. 
  The SDP, which split from the coalition in April in protest 
against maneuvering by its partners to create a new Diet bloc 
excluding the SDP, confirmed earlier in the day the party's 
policy of demanding Hata's resignation as a condition for its 
rejoining the fold. 
  Murayama is expected to urge Hata, who leads the first 
minority government in four decades, to resign along with his 
ministers at the planned meeting, coalition and SDP sources said. 
  Hata has so far rejected the call, but some coalition 
lawmakers Thursday voiced the view that he will announce his 
bowing out to pave the way for an early realliance. 
  The Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the largest opposition 
bloc, is poised to submit a no-confidence motion against the 
Hata cabinet after the budget passes the Diet later in the day. 
  The SDP turned down the LDP proposal for talks to form a 
joint government in a clear signal that it places top priority 
on the bid to rejoin hands with the coalition. 
  The SDP-coalition negotiations, based on the SDP's policy 
outline put forth Wednesday, centered on the bills for redrawing 
an electoral map in line with the political reform law passed in 
January and the proposed hike of the consumption tax. 
  The coalition called for an extension of the term for the 
current Diet session, which expires next Wednesday, for the 
passage of the bills, while the socialists argued it should be 
delayed to the next session, the sources said. 
  On the consumption tax, the coalition sought an SDP 
agreement 
to specify the size of the hike, but the socialists, who 
strongly objected to the introduction of the tax, rejected the 
request. 
  Meanwhile, Hata expressed strong hope for an SDP return to 
his camp. 
  "I would be happy if we can move toward a new politics along 
with the SDP. We have a seat open for them," Hata told a House 
of Councillors Budget Committee session. 
  In the face of growing prospects for the SDP's return to 
the ruling camp, three small reformist groups decided thursday 
to refuse any overtures to join the coalition unless it is made 
clear that the SDP will supply the prime minister. 
  New party Sakigake [Harbinger], which also broke ranks with 
the coalition, the Group Seiun, a splinter group from the Japan 
New Party (JNP), and Minshu no Kaze (Democratic Wind), another 
JNP defector club, also called for fresh policy-making talks 
among all the parties that have accepted invitations to join the 
coalition. 
  A senior Sakigake legislator, Hiroyuki Sonoda, in telephone 
talks with SDP Secretary General Wataru Kubo, said the SDP's 
policy outline is acceptable. 
  ``Sakigake would respond positively if the SDP tries to 
create a new coalition with Murayama as its head,'' he told Kubo. 
  Another Sakigake kingpin, Shusei Tanaka, told a press 
conference that the SDP's move to talk not only with the 
coalition but also with the LDP indicates the socialists have a 
radical realignment of the coalition in mind. 

</TEXT>

