<H3> <TI>   Hata, Murayama Fail To Patch Severed Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata, Murayama Fail To Patch Severed Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306133794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1328 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
and the head of the Social Democratic Party (SDP) [of Japan, 
SDPJ], a former coalition member, failed Thursday to find common 
ground to patch together the severed ties between the ruling 
coalition and the SDP. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama told reporters that talks 
with 
Hata did not bear fruit because sessions between the two sides 
over policy pacts are still continuing. 
  Coalition parties and the SDP, which are holding talks 
toward 
forming a policy agreement, could not find any middle ground in 
their reconciliation talks that would pave the way for the SDP 
to rejoin the alliance, official sources said. 
  Although Hata indicated Thursday that his minority cabinet 
would resign en masse, a condition the SDP has demanded for 
returning to the fold, off-and-on sessions between the two sides 
aimed at achieving a policy accord before forming a new 
coalition, hit an impasse over differences on tax reform, the 
sources said. 
  SDP Secretary General Wataru Kubo told reporters the party 
cannot immediately agree on the tax reform issue, including a 
hike in the current 3 percent consumption tax rate. 
  The coalition sought an SDP agreement to specify the size of 
the hike, but the socialists, who objected to the introduction 
of the tax, rejected the request. 
  The minority coalition and the SDP will continue to discuss 
the matter Friday, the sources said. 
  On Hata's remarks that he is ready to step down with all his 
cabinet ministers, Kubo said he takes the statement seriously 
and urged Hata to resign voluntarily en masse. 
  At a press conference after the long-overdue fiscal 1994 
budget cleared the Diet, Hata, 58, said he is ready to disband 
his cabinet if it is necessary to bring the SDP, a primary force 
in the previous coalition administration led by Morihiro 
Hosokawa, back to the camp. 
  The House of Representatives Diet Steering Committee, 
meanwhile, failed to set the timetable for the lower house to 
hold a plenary session to vote on a no-confidence motion against 
the Hata cabinet, which was submitted Thursday by the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). The LDP has said the minority 
administration does not reflect people's views. 
  The LDP, which was ousted by the coalition last August after 
dominating Japanese politics for 38 years, demanded that the 
lower chamber take a floor vote on the no-confidence motion on 
Friday but the coalition opposed it, saying talks with the SDP 
are continuing, the sources said. 
  It depends on SDP members whether the no-confidence motion 
passes the lower house, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

