<H3> <TI>   Upper House Budget Committee Approves Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Upper House Budget Committee Approves Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306070094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0603 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306070094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- The upper house budget 
committee on Thursday approved a long-delayed state budget for 
fiscal 1994, which started on April 1, which will go for passage 
at the house's plenary session later in the day. The approval 
of the 73.1 trillion yen state budget at the House of 
Councillors committee followed passage at the House of 
Representatives on June 8, 70 days overdue and three months 
after its was tabled in the Diet. 
  Diet debate on the budget, which was submitted to parliament 
on March 4, became snarled in a political squabble over former 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's personal financial affairs. 
Hosokawa stepped down in April because of the turmoil. 
  The nation's full spending budget includes 5.5 trillion yen 
for cuts in income and residential taxes to stimulate the 
economy. 
  Despite tight fiscal conditions, expenditures for public 
works projects were increased by 29.8 percent from the previous 
year to 11.1 trillion yen. Public works spending accounts for 
15.2 percent of the 40.9 trillion yen general operating 
expenditures, the core part of the budget that includes most 
outlays other than debt-servicing costs and tax allocations to 
local governments. Defense spending, in contrast, was raised by 
a scant 0.9 percent to 4.7 trillion yen. 

</TEXT>

