Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Enactment of Fiscal 1994 Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Enactment of Fiscal 1994 Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306080594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0757 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306080594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- The long-overdue fiscal 
1994 state budget became law Thursday [23 June], nearly three 
months after it should have come into force. 
  The House of Councillors gave a stamp of approval to the 
73.1 
trillion yen budget for the year that started April 1 at a 
plenary session after its budget committee cleared it earlier in 
the day. 
  Only three budgets took longer to enact than the fiscal 1994 
budget during the postwar period. 
  The government's budget plan was tabled in the Diet on March 
4 but had been left undebated for 80 days due to the political 
maelstrom over former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
personal financial affairs. The turmoil forced Hosokawa to step 
down in April. 
  But once deliberations started, the budget took an unusually 
short 23 days to become law. 
  The budget earmarks 40.9 trillion yen, or 2.3 percent more 
than the fiscal 1993 budget, for general operating expenditures, 
the core part of the budget that includes most outlays other 
than debt-servicing costs and tax allocations to local 
governments. 
  It features 5.5 trillion yen in income and residential tax 
reductions and sets aside 8.98 trillion yen, a 4.0 percent rise, 
for public works spending, both designed to shore up the ailing 
economy. 
  Outlays for defense are allowed to rise a scant 0.9 percent 
to 4.7 trillion yen while official development assistance was 
budgeted at 1.0 trillion yen, a 4.4 percent increase. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30067 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas121_a_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

