<H3> <TI>   House To Order Toshio Yamaguchi To Apologize </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    House To Order Toshio Yamaguchi To Apologize </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306110394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0959 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- The House of 
Representatives committee on discipline voted Thursday [23 June] 
to order former Labor Minister Toshio Yamaguchi to formally 
apologize in the Diet for his unruly actions at a lower house 
budget committee meeting last Friday. 
  Yamaguchi, a legislator without party affiliation, threw 
water at the seat of budget committee chairman Tsuruo Yamaguchi 
to protest the committee's decision to summon former Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for questioning over his financial 
affairs. Yamaguchi is not a committee member. 
  "His behavior essentially deserves barring from the house, 
but he also expressed some feelings of regret," Yoshio Yatsu, a 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) legislator, said in explaining 
the light punishment. 
  All committee members from the two main opposition groups, 
the LDP and the Social Democratic Party, voted for the motion. 
  The lower house is expected to adopt the committee's order 
for Yamaguchi to apologize at its next plenary session, which 
may be held as soon as Friday. 
  The House of Representatives decided earlier in the day to 
bring Yamaguchi before the committee on discipline for his 
misbehavior. 
  The last time disciplinary measures were taken against a 
lower house member was in June 1973, when Japanese Communist 
Party legislator Masako Kobayashi was barred from the chamber 
for 20 days. 

</TEXT>

