<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Survey on Politics, Leadership Conducted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Public Survey on Politics, Leadership Conducted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206070094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0607 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206070094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 22 KYODO -- Many mid-level government 
officials questioned believe it is time politicians exert 
stronger leadership to rein in Japan's central bureaucracy, but 
fewer believe there will be major change over the next 10 years, 
the National Personnel Authority said in a report released 
Wednesday [22 June]. 
  The Authority asked 102 division deputy director-class 
officials at ministries and agencies to judge the relationship 
between politicians and the administration. These young and 
prospective officials have received the Authority's 
administrative training from January to April. 
  Seventy-seven percent said "There are problems under the 
present conditions" and urged a change in the relationship, 50 
percent cited "weak political leadership over the 
administration" as a problem, and 49 percent supported the 
statement that "The administration interferes with matters which 
should be handled by politicians." Eighteen percent said that 
political pressure is "too high." 
  Multiple answers were allowed, so responses add up to more 
than 100 percent. 
  But only 17 percent voiced optimism that the political world 
will actually undergo major change during the next 10 years, 
while just 6 percent said so for the administration. 
  "Certain changes" in politics are anticipated by 54 percent, 
and in the administrative sphere by 45 percent. Almost a third 
believe that nothing will change in politics, while 49 percent 
fear that the administrative system will remain the same. 
  "The answers show that there is hope for a change of the 
current conditions as well as the awareness that such change 
will be difficult to realize," an authority official said in 
analyzing the survey results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

