<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Money Rates Remain `Unchanged' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Money Rates Remain `Unchanged' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306050094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0337 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306050094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- Money rates remained 
unchanged in Tokyo on Thursday [23 June] as the Bank of Japan 
took an almost neutral monetary stance. 
  In interbank trading, the unsecured overnight call rate was 
traded at 2 2/32 to 2 3/32 percent. 
  On the open market, the rate on newly issued three-month 
certificates of deposit was offered around 2.11-2.13 percent. 
  Considering the yen's recent gain against the dollar, the 
central bank's supply of funds was rather smaller than expected, 
said a dealer at a Japanese commercial bank. 
  Some expect the central bank to continue its monetary stance 
to stabilize longer-term interest rates for some time. 
  A dealer at a long-term credit bank said, "It will be a long 
time before the Bank of Japan tries to lead interest rates lower 
to check the yen's appreciation." 
  The bank of Japan injected 300 billion yen into the market 
by 
purchasing one-week discount bills worth 200 billion yen and by 
lending 100 billion yen to commercial banks, against the 
projected shortage of 320 billion yen for the day. 
  As of Wednesday, reserves by commercial banks in the central 
bank coffers were 300 billion yen over the required amount. 

</TEXT>

