<H3> <TI>   U.S., Japanese Lobbies on Surplus-to-GDP Ratio Cut </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., Japanese Lobbies on Surplus-to-GDP Ratio Cut </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306133994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1058 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2306133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 23 KYODO -- Business lobbies from Japan 
and the United States on Thursday [23 June] jointly urged that 
Japan's current account surplus be reduced to less than 2 
percent of its gross domestic product (GDP). 
  The Japan Association of Corporate Executives (Keizai 
Doyukai) and the Committee for Economic Development (CED) also 
agreed on their opposition to the setting of specific targets 
for Japan's imports from the U.S. 
  However, they said such targets would be effective if used 
in 
unbinding ways to gauge the openness of the Japanese market. 
  In a statement that described the Japan-U.S. relationship as 
the most important partnership in the world, the groups called 
on Japan to open its market and reduce its external imbalance. 
  The statement said the ratio of Japan's current account 
surplus to its GDP should be brought down to around 2 percent in 
fiscal 1997 and less than that thereafter. 
  Japan's current account surplus accounted for more than 3 
percent of the GDP in fiscal 1993 ended March 31. 
  The statement also requested more than 100 trillion yen be 
added to Japan's 430 trillion yen public works program for this 
decade. 

</TEXT>

