<H3> <TI>   Product Liability Bill Enacted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Product Liability Bill Enacted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206141494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1248 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 22 KYODO -- The House of Councillors on 
Wednesday [22 June] passed into law a product liability bill 
designed to protect consumers from accidents caused by defective 
products. 
  The law, which will go into effect next June, will be the 
first of its kind in Japan. 
  The law was passed by the powerful House of Representatives 
June 15. 
  In the course of debates in both chambers, a total of 16 
appendixes were attached to the bill to ease the burden on 
consumers seeking compensation in proving a product is defective. 
  Under the present system, consumers are required to prove 
negligence on the part of producers. 
  The new law leaves the decision on whether a product is 
defective up to the court. 
  Products covered by the law include medicines such as live 
vaccines and blood agents. 
  Manufacturers must now work out new measures to cope with 
future legal action taken by consumers seeking damages and 
compensation, industry officials said. 
  Consumer electronics makers have moved to consolidate and 
realign their in-house legal and intellectual property 
protection departments, they said. 
  Similar moves will be taken by pharmaceutical makers, they 
said. 
  The officials said medium and small enterprises have held 
seminars to get acquainted with the new law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30083 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas121_a_94030" </HT>


