Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Minister Welcomes Product Liability Bill </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Minister Welcomes Product Liability Bill </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206110594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1044 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 22 KYODO -- International Trade and 
Industry Minister Eijiro Hata on Wednesday [22 June] hailed the 
enactment of a bill to provide consumers with greater protection 
against accidents and injuries caused by defective products. 
  "The law is in line with the economic and social reality of 
Japan and is also well balanced internationally," Hata said in a 
statement. 
  The product liability bill was passed into law Wednesday by 
the House of Councillors after the second chamber's plenary 
session voted unanimously in favor of the bill. The more 
powerful House of Representatives already passed the bill June 
15. 
  Hata said his ministry will take adequate steps before the 
law goes into effect in one year, including dissemination of the 
law among concerned industries. 
  The product liability law will require consumers seeking 
compensation to simply prove that a product was faulty, rather 
than the present system whereby consumers must prove negligence 
by the maker. 
  But the law does not incorporate a provision holding makers 
liable for damages or injury through assumption of a link 
between the damage or injury and a defective product. 
  It took almost 20 years for the bill to be enacted since the 
Social Policy Council, an advisory body to the prime minister, 
began debate on better consumer protection from defective 
products in 1975. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

