<H3> <TI>   Panel Seeks Reform on Electric Power Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panel Seeks Reform on Electric Power Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206085494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0715 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2206085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 22 KYODO -- A Japanese Government panel 
on Wednesday [22 June] proposed easing rules and regulations as 
much as possible on safety and maintenance involved in electric 
power generation while maintaining the current security level. 
  The government should pursue a new security policy on 
electric power generation in response to the recent marked 
increase in safety and maintenance levels amid a rapid 
improvement in product quality, the Electricity Utility Industry 
Council, an advisory organ to the trade minister, said. 
  In an interim report presented to International Trade and 
Industry Minister Eijiro Hata, the council said the government's 
direct involvement in security of power generation should be 
reduced to a minimum necessary level. 
  How to maintain safety levels should thus basically be left 
to decision by each power supplier, with emphasis put on the 
principle of "self responsibility," the council said. 
  Government controls should be limited to prevention of 
pollution and other areas that affect public safety, it said. 
  Consumers of electricity should also share responsibility in 
maintaining security, the report said. 
  The council recommended further improvement in safety and 
maintenance levels through new technology development. 
  Standardization of power generation facilities and equipment 
should be promoted to upgrade overall security levels, it said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

