<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Hard-Line Conservative Forces' Denounced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Hard-Line Conservative Forces' Denounced </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2306091694 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1200 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2306091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1200 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to news reports, U.S. hard-line 
conservative forces have recently continued to wage an 
undisguised war frenzy against our Republic. 
  According to a Voice of America report on 20 June, two U.S. 
senators, including Senator McCain, gave a news conference after 
their junket to South Korea, and advocated imposing tough 
sanctions against us and reinforcing U.S. forces in South Korea. 
They even made provocative, violent remarks, in an undisguised 
way, insisting that the United States launch a selective 
military strike against us. 
  Prior to this, in a television interview, Representative 
Hamilton, chairman of the U.S. House Foreign Affairs Committee, 
remarked that there is a limit to U.S. patience. He said 
emphatically: It is necessary to complete the (?threat) 
potential of the ROK and U.S. Armed Forces and to make the 
intensification of sanctions a way to solve the issue on a 
priority basis. 
  In recent days, a spokesman for the U.S. Defense Department 
has found fault with us by saying that our measure of 
withdrawing from the International Atomic Energy Agency is 
making the situation more dangerous. He made an undisguised 
remark to rapidly reinforce U.S. Armed Forces in South Korea and 
additionally deploy U.S. military airplanes and an aircraft 
carrier to the area near the Korean peninsula. 
  THE WASHINGTON TIMES, a U.S. newspaper, has reported that 
the 
U.S. Defense Department has recently made an in-depth 
examination of ways to conduct a rapid dispatch of U.S. troops 
and U.S. fighter planes and a further dispatch of artillery 
detection radar, while additionally dispatching military 
intelligence experts to South Korea. 
  According to THE WALL STREET JOURNAL, a U.S. newspaper, U.S. 
Assistant Secretary of Defense Ashton has made it public that 
the United States is further reinforcing U.S. forces in South 
Korea with modern weapons and combat equipment. 

</TEXT>

