<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-121-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Rejects U.S. Demand on Creating IPA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Rejects U.S. Demand on Creating IPA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2206172694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Jun 
94 Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2206172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. Government has demanded that the Japanese 
Government set up a Investment-Promotion Agency [IPA] designed 
to facilitate foreign firms' direct investment in Japan. It has 
asked Japan to set up an agency which specializes in carrying 
out intermediary work on foreign investment in Japan and in 
providing foreign companies with information on loans by the 
Japan Development Bank [JDB] and other banks. It has also 
demanded that Japan promote the deregulation of investment with 
a new agency playing a leading role. 
  The establishment of the new government agency is one of the 
U.S. demands in connection with the Japanese-U.S. economic 
framework talks. The U.S. Government has maintained that in 
order to increase direct investment in Japan, the Japanese 
Government needs to find foreign firms which are enthusiastic 
about doing business in Japan, as well as to provide information 
on JDB loans and favorable treatment in terms of taxation. It 
has demanded that the Japanese Government set up a general 
agency designed to provide such services and to formulate new 
programs for promoting investment. 
  Meanwhile, the Japanese Government has rejected the U.S. 
demand, saying: "The establishment of the new government agency 
runs counter to the current move to promote administrative 
reform." It has claimed that the United States should set up a 
contact office for promoting investment in Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-30110 </DOCNO>
