<H3> <TI>   Government Urged To Intervene in Money Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Urged To Intervene in Money Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2406084494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 10 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2406084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The yen (Y)-dollar rate temporarily plunged below 
Y100 to a dollar on 22 June. In this regard, top officials of 
the four economic organizations pointed out that "it is a big 
shock to the economic world because there were signs that the 
Japanese economy was about to begin recovering from stagnation 
and that the yen exchange rate was becoming stable," (according 
to Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of the Japan Federation of 
Economic Organizations). The top officials demanded that the 
government take concrete measures, including income tax 
reduction and deregulation, to reduce Japan's trade surplus. 
They also asked the monetary authorities to strongly intervene 
in the money market. 
  Chairman Toyoda also said: "An appropriate level of the yen- 
dollar exchange rate is between Y110 and Y120. Actual gross 
national product for fiscal 1994 will drop by 0.8 percent if the 
exchange rate of Y100 to the dollar continues for a year." 
  Ken Hayami, chairman of the Japan Federation of Employers 
Associations, stressed: "We may even have industrial 
stagnation, increased unemployment, and social unrest if we 
allow yen's abnormally high value, which does not reflect the 
actual economic conditions." Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the 
Japan Chamber o Commerce and Industry, expressed his concern, 
saying that "it will be a serious blow to small-to-medium-sized 
enterprises." 
  Yu Hayami, representative secretary of the Japanese 
Association of Corporate Executives, stated: "The dollar fell 
against all currencies as a result of apprehension about 
possible inflation in the United States and other things. Even 
the United States cannot tolerate the dollar's further decline." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

